DATA COLLECTION PROCEDURES: 
 
The authors have also shared a preview of the qualtrics script used in the original study. This is 
available here: 
https://stanfordgsb.ca1.qualtrics.com/jfe/preview/SV_9NV7HmXcBsIMrTn?Q_SurveyVersionID=
current&Q_CHL=preview 
 
Participants, recruited via Amazon’s Mechanical Turk (paid $5 each) will first complete a task, based 
on items in the self-concept clarity scale (Campbell et al. 1996), that is designed to lower or heighten 
participants’ self-concept clarity. Participants will be randomly assigned to a clear or conflicted 
condition, and read a prompt that will ask them to think of a time they had a clear or conflicted sense 
of themselves: “There are times when you have [don’t have] a clear and con-sistent sense of who 
you really are, when you feel like you[don’t] truly know what you are like. You have 
consistent[conflicting] views about yourself that do not change overtime [shift from day to day]. For 
example, you may have felt clear [conflicted] and sure [unsure] about particular traits or aspects of 
yourself or been in a situation that dis-played that you had a clear [conflicting] sense of yourself. 
Please take a few minutes to recall and immerse yourself in a time when you felt that you had [didn’t 
have] a clear and consistent view of who you really were. Please describe this in as much detail as 
possible—what happened, how you felt, etc.” 
 
Participants will then complete the same  brief filler task used in the original (Wichman, Brunner, and 
Weary 2008). 
 

Participants will then read a brief hypothetical scenario, in which they will be asked to imagine that 
“An acquaintance you met only recently mentions that they really enjoyed a certain movie. You look 
up the movie to see what other people thought of it. Imagine that you see one of the following ratings 
for the movie.” Below this prompt, participants will see a bimodal or unimodal distribution. The 
product rating distributions were designed to be bimodal or unimodal but have identical means. The 
bimodal distribution consists of two clusters of ratings: one cluster at the five-star rating and the 
other cluster at the one-star rating, with fewer ratings in between. The unimodal distribution has one 
main cluster of ratings with the ratings tapering off toward the lower tail.  
 
 
After viewing the movie information, participants will evaluate the movie on a seven-point scale of 
perceived quality (good/bad), likelihood of purchasing the movie (likely/unlikely), and likelihood of 
seeing the movie (likely/unlikely). They will also be asked if they were able to see the image 
(distribution of ratings). 
